{{more footnotes|date=December 2017}}
[[File:Emiliea Barabancea (stânga).jpg|thumb]]
'''Family resemblance''' refers to physical similarities shared between close relatives, especially between [[parents]] and children and between [[siblings]].<ref>[http://www.abroadintheyard.com/dna-family-resemblance-across-generations/ Who Do You Look Like? DNA and Family Resemblance Across Generations]</ref> In [[psychology]], the similarities of [[personality]] are also observed.

==Genetics==
[[Heritability]], defined as a measure of family resemblance, causes traits to be genetically passed from parents to offspring ([[heredity]]), allowing evolutionarily advantageous traits to persist through generations.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Dolinska B | title = Resemblance and investment in children | language = fr | journal = International Journal of Psychology | volume = 48 | issue = 3 | pages = 285–90 | date = June 2013 | pmid = 22385106 | doi = 10.1080/00207594.2011.645482 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tremblay BL, Guénard F, Lamarche B, Pérusse L, Vohl MC | title = Familial resemblances in human whole blood transcriptome | journal = BMC Genomics | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages = 300 | date = April 2018 | pmid = 29703154 | pmc = 5921553 | doi = 10.1186/s12864-018-4698-6 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bochud M | title = Estimating heritability from nuclear family and pedigree data | journal = Methods in Molecular Biology | volume = 850 | pages = 171–86 | date = 2012 | pmid = 22307699 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-61779-555-8_10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = The Princeton Guide to Evolution|last=Brodie|first=Edmond | name-list-format = vanc |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2014 |isbn=|location=|pages=221–229}}</ref> Despite sharing parents, siblings do not inherit identical genes, making [[Twin study|studies on identical twins]] (who have identical DNA) especially effective at analyzing the role genetics play in [[Phenotype|phenotypic]] similarity.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite journal | vauthors = Plomin R, Daniels D | title = Why are children in the same family so different from one another? | journal = International Journal of Epidemiology | volume = 40 | issue = 3 | pages = 563–82 | date = June 2011 | pmid = 21807642 | pmc = 3147063 | doi = 10.1093/ije/dyq148 }}</ref>  Studies have found that generational resemblance of many [[phenotypic trait]]s results from the inheritance of multiples genes that collectively influence a trait ([[Genetic variance|additive genetic variance]]).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Polderman TJ, Benyamin B, de Leeuw CA, Sullivan PF, van Bochoven A, Visscher PM, Posthuma D | title = Meta-analysis of the heritability of human traits based on fifty years of twin studies | language = En | journal = Nature Genetics | volume = 47 | issue = 7 | pages = 702–9 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 25985137 | doi = 10.1038/ng.3285 }}</ref> There is evidence of heritability in personality traits. For example, one study found that approximately half of personality differences in high-school aged fraternal and identical twins were due to [[genetic variation]] - and another study suggests that no one personality trait is more heritable than another.<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ahern|first=Frank M.|last2=Johnson|first2=Ronald C.|last3=Wilson|first3=James R.|last4=McClearn|first4=Gerald E.|last5=Vandenberg|first5=Steven G. | name-list-format = vanc |date= May 1982 |title=Family resemblances in personality |journal=Behavior Genetics|language=en|volume=12|issue=3|pages=261–280|doi=10.1007/bf01067847|issn=0001-8244}}</ref>

==Environment==
Family resemblance is also shaped by environmental factors, [[temperature]], [[light]], [[Human nutrition|nutrition]], exposure to [[drug]]s, the time that different family members spend in shared and non-shared environments, are examples of factors found to influence phenotype.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/environmental-influences-on-gene-expression-536|title=Environmental Influences on Gene Expression {{!}} Learn Science at Scitable|website=www.nature.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite journal | vauthors = Plomin R, Daniels D | title = Why are children in the same family so different from one another? | journal = International Journal of Epidemiology | volume = 40 | issue = 3 | pages = 563–82 | date = June 2011 | pmid = 21807642 | doi = 10.1093/ije/dyq148 | pmc = 3147063 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WhUvDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA53 |title=Evolutionary Theory: Fringe or Central to Psychological Science|last=Sulikowski|first=Danielle | name-list-format = vanc |date=2016-08-08|publisher=Frontiers Media SA|isbn=9782889199204}}</ref>  Phenotypes found to be largely environmentally determined in humans include [[personality]], [[Human height|height]], and [[Human body weight|weight]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eysenck|first=H. J.|date= March 1990 |title=Genetic and Environmental Contributions to Individual Differences: The Three Major Dimensions of Personality |journal=Journal of Personality |volume=58|issue=1|pages=245–261|doi=10.1111/j.1467-6494.1990.tb00915.x }}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/why-are-we-getting-taller/|title=Why are we getting taller as a species?|work=Scientific American|access-date=2018-08-09|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ourworldindata.org/human-height|title=Human Height|website=Our World in Data|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref> Twin studies have shown that more than half of the variation in a few major aspects of personality are environmentally determined, and that environmental factors even affect traits like [[immune response]] and how children handle [[Stress (biology)|stress]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sirota M, Willemsen G, Sundar P, Pitts SJ, Potluri S, Prifti E, Kennedy S, Ehrlich SD, Neuteboom J, Kluft C, Malone KE, Cox DR, de Geus EJ, Boomsma DI | title = Effect of genome and environment on metabolic and inflammatory profiles | journal = PLOS One | volume = 10 | issue = 4 | pages = e0120898 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25853885 | pmc = 4390246 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0120898 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Schreiber JE, Shirtcliff E, Van Hulle C, Lemery-Chalfant K, Klein MH, Kalin NH, Essex MJ, Goldsmith HH | title = Environmental influences on family similarity in afternoon cortisol levels: twin and parent-offspring designs | journal = Psychoneuroendocrinology | volume = 31 | issue = 9 | pages = 1131–7 | date = October 2006 | pmid = 16997489 | pmc = 2754130 | doi = 10.1016/j.psyneuen.2006.07.005 }}</ref> Additionally, anomalous findings, such as [[second-degree relative]]s of [[Alcoholism|alcoholics]], showing surprising similarities to them have led some researchers’ attempts in generating better models that account for the environmental impacts on influences like cultural inheritance, [[Family|family structure]] and [[Head of Household|head of household]], which have been shown to influence family resemblance.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cloninger CR, Rice J, Reich T | title = Multifactorial inheritance with cultural transmission and assortative mating. III. Family structure and the analysis of separation experiments | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 31 | issue = 3 | pages = 366–88 | date = May 1979 | pmid = 572636 | pmc = 1685778 }}</ref>

