'''Meg-John Barker''' (born 23 June 1974) is an author, speaker, consultant, and activist-academic. They have written a number of anti self-help books on the topics of relationships, sex, and gender, as well as the popular comic book Queer: A Graphic History, and the book The Psychology of Sex. They are the writer of the relationships book and blog Rewriting the Rules, and they have a podcast with sex educator Justin Hancock.

Barker is currently a Senior Lecturer in [[Psychology]] at the [[Open University]] in the United Kingdom with a focus on [[psychotherapy]]. Barker holds a PhD in Psychology from the [[University of Nottingham]], and is also a [[UKCP]] accredited [[psychotherapist]] specializing in [[sex therapy]] and [[relationship counseling]].

Barker has written and/or edited some of the first academic collections on open [[non-monogamy]], [[bisexuality]], [[non-binary gender]] and [[BDSM]]. They were editor of the journal ''Psychology & Sexuality'' from 2010 to 2017, and lead author of ''The Bisexuality Report'' and the [[BACP]] document on Gender, Sexual, and Relationship Diversity.

Barker's pronouns are singular they/them.

==Early life and education==
Barker was born in Hull, England, on 23 June 1974, grew up in [[Bradford]],  and  holds a PhD<ref>{{cite book |last=Barker |first=M. |date=1999 |title=Student Loneliness: An Exploratory Investigation. PhD. Psychology |publisher=University of Nottingham. Unpublished}}</ref> in [[Psychology]] from the [[University of Nottingham]]. After teaching at  a number of higher education institutions Barker settled at the [[Open University]] in 2008, having also qualified with an MA in [[Psychotherapy]] from the [[University of Sheffield]] and trained at the major [[National Health Service|NHS]] sexual and relationship clinic at [[Guy's Hospital]] for several years.

==Recent career==
Barker's   main area of expertise is human sexuality, gender and romantic relationships, with a focus on the experiences of people in sexual, gender and relationship communities  located outside the mainstream – particularly [[polyamorous]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Clarke |first1=V. |last2=Ellis |first2=S. J. |last3=Peel |first3=E. |last4=Riggs |first4=D. W. |date=2010 |title=Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Trans and Queer Psychology: An Introduction. |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521700184}}</ref> [[Kink (sexual)|kink]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Weeks |first=J. |date=2011 |title=The Languages of Sexuality. |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0415375733}}</ref> [[non-binary]]<ref name="Social Constructionism">{{citation | title=Burr, V. (2015). Social Constructionism (3rd Edition). Routledge {{ISBN|978-1848721920}}}}</ref> and [[Bisexual community|bisexual communities]]. Theoretically their work draws on [[social constructionism]], [[existentialism]] and [[Buddhist philosophy]]. Barker, with co-author Darren Langdridge,   has published two   edited collections on [[sadomasochism]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barker |first1=M. |last2=Langdridge |first2=D. |date=2013 |title=Safe, Sane and Consensual: Contemporary Perspectives on Sadomasochism |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1137338372}}</ref> and on [[non-monogamy]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barker |first1=M. |last2=Langdridge |first2=D. |date=2012 |title=Understanding Non-Monogamies |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0415652964}}</ref>  and a recent book for mental health professionals (co-authored with Christina Richards). Barker founded the journal of ''Psychology & Sexuality''<ref>{{cite journal |title=Psychology & Sexuality |publisher=Taylor & Francis |issn=1941-9899 |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/toc/rpse20/current}}</ref> together with Langdridge in 2010, and they co-edited it until 2017. Barker co-organized the Critical Sexology<ref name="Critical Sexology">{{citation |title=Critical Sexology |url=http://criticalsexology.org.uk}}</ref> series from 2006 to 2018, and BiReCon<ref>{{citation |title=BiReCon |url=https://bisexualresearch.wordpress.com/birecon/}}</ref> (a biennial research conference which takes place prior to the annual [[BiCon (UK)|BiCon]] event).

===Writing===
Barker coined the phrase ‘anti self-help’ to describe self-help materials which locate the struggles that people have in their wider societal structures and cultural messages rather than in them as individuals[12]. Barker’s anti self-help books aim to help people to navigate their relationship with wider sociocultural understandings, rather than viewing themselves as a problem that needs fixing. They have produced books applying this approach to relationships<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barker |first1=M.-J. |date=2018 |title=Rewriting the Rules: An Anti Self-help Guide to Love, Sex and Relationships. Second edition. |publisher=Routledge. |isbn=978-1138676497}}</ref>, sex (with Justin Hancock)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barker |first1=M.-J. |last2=Hancock |first2=J. |date=2017 |title=Enjoy Sex (How, When and If You Want To): A Practical and Inclusive Guide. |publisher=Icon Books. |isbn=978-1785780806}}</ref>, and gender (with Alex Iantaffi)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Iantaffi |first1=A. |last2=Barker |first2=M.-J. |date=2017  |title=How to Understand Your Gender: A Practical Guide for Exploring Who You Are. |publisher=Jessica Kingsley. |isbn=978-1785927461}}</ref>, as well as producing graphic-novel style non-fiction books and zines on queer<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barker |first1=M.-J. |last2=Scheele |first2=J. |date=2016 |title=Queer: A Graphic History. |publisher=Icon Books. |isbn=978-1785780714}}</ref>, mindfulness and other topics<ref>{{citation |title=Zines |url=https://www.rewriting-the-rules.com/zines/}}</ref>, and a podcast on sex and relationships<ref>{{citation |title=Meg-John and Justin |url=https://megjohnandjustin.com/}}</ref>.

===Consulting===
Barker has a background in psychotherapy, and led production on the [[Open University]] module Counselling: Exploring Fear and Sadness<ref name="Counseling: Exploring Fear and Sadness">{{citation | title=Counseling: Exploring Fear and Sadness | url=http://www.open.ac.uk/socialsciences/study/tasters/d240.php}}</ref>. They are trained in [[existential therapy|existential psychotherapy]] and [[mindfulness]] with books on the latter<ref>{{cite book |last=Barker |first=M. |date=2013 |title=Mindful Counselling and Psychotherapy. |publisher=Sage Publications. |isbn=978-1446211113}}</ref> developing the approaches of social mindfulness and mindful sex and relationship therapy (MSRT)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brotto |first1=L. |last2=Barker |first2=M. |date=2014 |title=Mindfulness in Sexual and Relationship Therapy. |publisher=Routledge. |isbn=978-0415736961}}</ref>. Their practice now takes the form of peer-to-peer consulting and mentoring with writers, practitioners, activists, and organisers, with a focus on relationships with self, others, and the wider world.

===Activism===
Barker's activism in the area of [[LGBT]]&[[Queer|Q]] rights has been recognized by placement   in the top 40 of The Independent on Sunday newspaper's Pink List,<ref name="The Independent on Sunday Pink List 2013">{{citation | title=The Independent on Sunday Pink List 2013 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-independent-on-sundays-pink-list-2013-8876183.html}}</ref> and Rainbow List.<ref name="The Independent on Sunday Rainbow List 2014">{{citation | title=The Independent on Sunday Rainbow List 2014 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/therainbowlist/rainbow-list-2014-1-to-100-9848457.html}}</ref>  Barker was one of the founder members of BiUK, the organization for bisexual research and activism.<ref name="BiUK">{{citation | title=BiUK | url=http://www.biuk.org/ |isbn=978-0415517638}}</ref> This group wrote the international guidelines for academics studying bisexuality (published in [[Journal of Bisexuality]]) and produced ''The Bisexuality Report'' which informs UK policy and practice regarding bisexuality based on the evidence regarding [[biphobia]], [[bisexual invisibility]], and [[mental health]]<ref name="Bisexual stigma and adverse mental health">{{citation | title=Bisexual stigma and adverse mental health | url=http://www.bps.org.uk/news/bisexual-stigma-and-adverse-mental-health}}</ref> In 2013, Barker took home an Erotic Award in the academic category for the book Rewriting the Rules, as reported in [[Times Higher Education]]<ref name="Times Higher Education, Erotic Awards, Academic Category, 2013">{{citation | title=Times Higher Education, Erotic Awards, Academic Category 2013 | url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/erotic-awards-2013-honour-for-open-university-academic/2004694.article}}</ref>. Their current activism focuses on trans and non-binary communities<ref name="The Indie. Trans activist. 2018">{{citation | title=The Indie. Trans activists. 2018 | url=https://www.indy100.com/article/trans-lives-shon-faye-juno-dawson-riley-carter-india-willoughby-travis-alabanza-annie-wallace-8099866}}</ref>.

